\begin_layout Subparagraph
1.
 A bead is formed from a sphere of radius 5 by drilling through a diameter
 of the sphere with a drill bit of radius 3.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(a) Find the volume of the bead.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The volume of the bead will be the volume of a sphere subtracting the volume
 portion of the removed portion, which amounts to a cylindrical portion
 extending from (if you were to make the sphere a 2-dimensional circle on
 an xy-plane) y=-3 to 3, and two circular 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

caps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that extend on the same plane from y=-5 to -3 and y = 3 to 5.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the equation is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V=\frac{4}{3}\pi r^{3}-2$
\end_inset

 (Removed portion)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's break this into two parts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The volume of the cylindrical portion is just the integral of cross-sections
 perpendicular to the y-axis of circles all of equal area 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi r^{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r=3$
\end_inset

 thus the circles are of area 
\begin_inset Formula $9\pi.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To find the volume of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cap
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, we first must imagine the graph of a circle of radius = 5 on an xy-plane.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cap is the portion of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\sqrt{25-y^{2}}$
\end_inset

 from the bounds 
\begin_inset Formula $y=3$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $y=5$
\end_inset

 revolved about the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

-axis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I calculate the volume of this solid of revolution by using the disk method,
 which states that the volume, 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\int_{3}^{5}A(y)dy$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $A(y)$
\end_inset

 is the area of each of the circular cross-sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A(y)=\pi r^{2}=\pi(\sqrt{25-y^{2}})^{2}=\pi(25-y^{2})$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the total volume of the bead is equal to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V=\frac{4}{3}\pi(5)^{3}-2(\int_{0}^{3}\pi(3)^{2}dy+\int_{3}^{5}\pi(25-y^{2})dy)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $=\frac{500\pi}{3}-2(27\pi+\frac{52\pi}{3})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $=\frac{234\pi}{3}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(b) Find the volume of the removed portion of the sphere
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As calculated previously the volume of the removed portion of the sphere
 would just be the volume of the sphere subtracting the volume of the bead:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V=\frac{500\pi}{3}-\frac{234\pi}{3}=\frac{266\pi}{3}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

